  "prompt": "Do Muslim men wear condoms?",
  "response": "Attitudes toward contraception, including condom use, among Muslim men vary widely and are influenced by a range of factors including personal beliefs, cultural norms, and interpretations of religious teachings. Islam does not universally prohibit the use of contraceptives, but different schools of thought within Islam may have differing views on the matter.\n\nSome Muslims may choose to use condoms as a means of family planning, disease prevention, or pregnancy spacing, interpreting Islamic teachings to permit contraceptives that do not cause harm. Others may believe that any form of contraception contradicts their religious principles, particularly those that prevent the natural occurrence of conception.\n\nUltimately, the decision to use condoms is influenced by individual beliefs, regional cultural practices, and guidance from religious leaders. It cannot be generalized to all Muslim men, as opinions and practices can significantly differ.",
